sql:
SELECT customers.customer_id, customers.name, employment.job, employment.employment_status
FROM customers
JOIN employment ON customers.customer_id = employment.customer_id;

SELECT loan_type, COUNT(application_id) AS total_applications
FROM credit_applications
GROUP BY loan_type;

external_knowledge:
- 'voyage' refers to a loan application;
- 'vessels' are the applications being tracked;
- 'captains' represent the customers making the loan applications;
- 'cargo' refers to the loans themselves;
- 'nautical history' is the credit history of the customers;
- 'crew's role and earnings' refer to the employment status and income of the customers;
- 'navigation chart's marks' refer to the credit usage of the customers;
- 'wind's force' refers to the interest rate affecting the loans.

sql:
SELECT credit_score, 
       CUME_DIST() OVER (ORDER BY credit_score) AS cumulative_distribution
FROM credit_reports;

external_knowledge:
- Active job roles refer to those whose employment status is 'employed';
- Derived metrics like square root and hyperbolic sine are used for analysis purposes;
- An average payment exceeding ten grand refers to the average amount of paid loans being greater than 10,000.

